    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Albuminocytologic dissociation</b> is a specific cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) finding characterized by an <u>elevated protein level</u> in the presence of a normal (or near-normal) white blood cell count, classically associated with the inflammation and nerve root demyelination of [[guillain_barre_syndrome]].</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism:</b> Inflammation of the spinal nerve roots allows plasma proteins to leak into the CSF, but the blood-nerve barrier remains intact enough to prevent significant cellular infiltration.</li><li><b>Diagnostic Criteria:</b> Elevated CSF protein (>45 mg/dL) with normal WBC count (<10 cells/¬µL).</li><li><b>Associations:</b> The hallmark laboratory finding of [[guillain_barre_syndrome]] (Acute Inflammatory Demyelinating Polyneuropathy).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> If the vignette describes ascending paralysis and asks for the CSF finding, look for \"High protein, low cells.\"</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Albuminocytologic dissociation</b> reflects the breakdown of the blood-nerve barrier at the level of the nerve roots, allowing protein leakage without pleocytosis, distinguishing [[guillain_barre_syndrome]] from infectious etiologies like [[meningitis]].</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
