    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Lateral Geniculate Nucleus (LGN)</b> is a specific sensory relay nucleus within the [[thalamus]] that receives visual information from the [[optic_tract]] and projects it via the optic radiations to the [[primary_visual_cortex]] (calcarine sulcus) in the occipital lobe.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Input:</b> [[optic_tract]] (carrying fibers from the ipsilateral temporal retina and contralateral nasal retina).</li><li><b>Output:</b> Optic radiations (Geniculocalcarine tract) to the [[primary_visual_cortex]] (V1).</li><li><b>Function:</b> Processing and relaying visual data (Vision).</li><li><b>Structure:</b> 6 layers; Layers 1, 4, 6 receive contralateral input; Layers 2, 3, 5 receive ipsilateral input.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Mnemonic: <b>L</b> is for <b>L</b>ight (Vision) = <b>L</b>GN.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Lateral Geniculate Nucleus</b> is the primary thalamic processing center for the visual system, acting as the gateway between the retina and the [[visual_cortex]].</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph LR; A[Retina] --> B[Optic Nerve]; B --> C[Optic Chiasm]; C --> D[Optic Tract]; D --> E[Lateral Geniculate Nucleus]; E --> F[Optic Radiations]; F --> G[Primary Visual Cortex];"
    },
    "connections": [
