    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Charcot-Bouchard microaneurysms</b> are minute aneurysms that form in the small, penetrating vessels of the brain (specifically the [[lenticulostriate_arteries]]) due to <u>chronic uncontrolled hypertension</u>, serving as the primary cause of spontaneous deep [[intraparenchymal_hemorrhage]].</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Chronic [[hypertension]] leads to lipohyalinosis and fibrinoid necrosis of small vessel walls, weakening them and causing micro-dilations.</li><li><b>Location:</b> Deep brain structures: [[basal_ganglia]] (putamen), [[thalamus]], pons, and cerebellum.</li><li><b>Clinical Consequence:</b> Rupture leads to hypertensive intraparenchymal hemorrhage (hemorrhagic stroke), causing contralateral hemiparesis or sensory loss depending on location.</li><li><b>Imaging:</b> Too small to be seen on angiography (unlike [[saccular_aneurysm]]); diagnosis is inferred by the presence of deep hemorrhage on CT.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Contrast with Saccular (Berry) aneurysms: Charcot-Bouchard = <b>Chronic Hypertension</b> (small vessels, intraparenchymal bleed); Berry = <b>Structural defect</b> (Circle of Willis, Subarachnoid bleed).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Charcot-Bouchard microaneurysms</b> are the pathological link between chronic hypertension and deep hemorrhagic strokes, specifically affecting the lenticulostriate arteries supplying the basal ganglia.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Chronic Hypertension] --> B[Lipohyalinosis]; B --> C[Vessel Wall Weakening]; C --> D[Charcot-Bouchard Aneurysm]; D --> E[Rupture]; E --> F[Intraparenchymal Hemorrhage];"
    },
