  "ethosuximide": {
    "title": "Ethosuximide",
    "primaryType": "substance",
    "tags": [
      "Pharmacology",
      "Neurology",
      "Anticonvulsants",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Pharmacology",
      "Neurology Drugs",
      "Anticonvulsants"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Ethosuximide</b> is a narrow-spectrum <i>anticonvulsant</i> that acts by blocking <u>T-type calcium channels</u> in thalamic neurons, specifically indicated for the treatment of [[absence_seizure]].</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism:</b> Blocks voltage-gated <b>T-type Ca<sup>2+</sup> channels</b> in the [[thalamus]], disrupting the thalamocortical oscillations responsible for absence seizures.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> First-line monotherapy for [[absence_seizure]].</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> GI distress (nausea/vomiting), fatigue, headache, itching, and rarely [[stevens_johnson_syndrome]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Remember \"<b>E</b>thosuximide for <b>E</b>veryone's <b>F</b>avorite <b>G</b>eneralized <b>H</b>eart-throb\" (EFGH: <b>E</b>thosuximide, <b>F</b>atigue, <b>G</b>I distress, <b>H</b>eadache). Or simply: It SUCKS (Etho<b>sux</b>imide) to have Silent Seizures.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Ethosuximide</b> is the drug of choice for [[absence_seizure]] because it specifically targets the <mark>T-type calcium channels</mark> in the thalamus that generate the characteristic 3 Hz spike-and-wave rhythm.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
