    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Acalculia</b> is an acquired neurological deficit characterized by the <u>inability to perform simple mathematical calculations</u>, classically associated with lesions to the <b>dominant parietal lobe</b> (specifically the angular gyrus).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Localization:</b> Dominant (usually Left) [[parietal_lobe]] (Angular Gyrus).</li><li><b>Associations:</b> A core component of [[gerstmann_syndrome]] (along with agraphia, finger agnosia, and left-right disorientation).</li><li><b>Etiology:</b> Stroke (e.g., [[middle_cerebral_artery]] infarct), tumor, or neurodegeneration.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> If a patient cannot subtract 7 from 100 serially and has right-left confusion, suspect a dominant parietal lesion.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Acalculia</b> is a localizing sign for <b>dominant parietal lobe</b> dysfunction, most famously as part of the tetrad of [[gerstmann_syndrome]].</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
