  "accessory_nerve": {
    "title": "Accessory Nerve (CN XI)",
    "primaryType": "structure",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Anatomy",
      "Cranial Nerves",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology",
      "Cranial Nerves",
      "CN XI"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Accessory Nerve (CN XI)</b> is a purely motor cranial nerve that originates from the upper cervical spinal cord, enters the skull via the foramen magnum, and exits via the [[jugular_foramen]] to innervate the <b>sternocleidomastoid</b> (SCM) and <b>trapezius</b> muscles.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Function:</b> Head turning (SCM) and shoulder shrugging (Trapezius).</li><li><b>Course:</b> Spinal roots C1-C5 &rarr; Foramen Magnum &rarr; Jugular Foramen &rarr; Muscles.</li><li><b>Lesion Findings:</b> <br> - <b>LMN Lesion:</b> Ipsilateral shoulder droop (weak trapezius), difficulty turning head to the <u>contralateral</u> side (weak ipsilateral SCM).<br> - <b>Winged Scapula:</b> Can occur (lateral winging) but distinct from Long Thoracic Nerve injury (medial winging).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> To test the <b>Right</b> SCM, the patient turns their head to the <b>Left</b>. A Right CN XI lesion causes weakness turning head to the Left.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>CN XI</b> is unique for its spinal origin and cranial exit; damage results in ipsilateral shoulder weakness and difficulty turning the head away from the lesion.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[C1-C5 Spinal Roots] --> B[Foramen Magnum]; B --> C[Jugular Foramen]; C --> D[Sternocleidomastoid]; C --> E[Trapezius];"
