  "acetylcholine": {
    "title": "Acetylcholine (ACh)",
    "primaryType": "substance",
    "tags": [
      "Neuroscience",
      "Physiology",
      "Pharmacology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neuroscience",
      "Neurotransmitters",
      "Cholinergics"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Acetylcholine (ACh)</b> is a major neurotransmitter synthesized from choline and acetyl-CoA that acts on <u>nicotinic</u> (ligand-gated ion channels) and <u>muscarinic</u> (G-protein coupled) receptors to mediate motor control, autonomic functions, and cognition.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Sites of Action:</b><br> 1. <b>NMJ:</b> Somatic motor neurons (Nicotinic).<br> 2. <b>Autonomic Ganglia:</b> Both Sympathetic and Parasympathetic (Nicotinic).<br> 3. <b>Parasympathetic Effectors:</b> Smooth muscle, glands, heart (Muscarinic).<br> 4. <b>CNS:</b> Basal nucleus of Meynert (Cognition/Memory).</li><li><b>Synthesis/Degradation:</b> Made by Choline Acetyltransferase (ChAT); degraded by [[acetylcholinesterase]] (AChE).</li><li><b>Pathology:</b> Decreased in [[alzheimer_disease]] and [[huntington_disease]]; Increased in [[parkinson_disease]] (relative to dopamine).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> In the Sympathetic NS, ACh is the neurotransmitter at the ganglion AND at the <b>Sweat Glands</b> (muscarinic) and <b>Adrenal Medulla</b> (nicotinic).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Acetylcholine</b> is the primary neurotransmitter of the parasympathetic nervous system and the neuromuscular junction; its levels are critically reduced in [[alzheimer_disease]] and targeted by AChE inhibitors.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Choline + Acetyl-CoA] -->|ChAT| B[Acetylcholine]; B -->|Release| C[Synaptic Cleft]; C -->|AChE| D[Choline + Acetate]; C --> E[Nicotinic/Muscarinic Receptors];"
    },
