    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Achilles Reflex</b> (Ankle Jerk) is a deep tendon reflex mediated by the <u>S1 and S2</u> nerve roots (primarily S1), where striking the Achilles tendon causes plantar flexion of the foot.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Nerve Roots:</b> <b>S1</b>, S2.</li><li><b>Nerve:</b> [[tibial_nerve]].</li><li><b>Action:</b> Plantar flexion of the foot via the gastrocnemius/soleus muscles.</li><li><b>Clinical Significance:</b><br> - <i>Decreased/Absent:</i> S1 radiculopathy (e.g., herniated disc), peripheral neuropathy (e.g., diabetes), [[guillain_barre_syndrome]].<br> - <i>Delayed Relaxation:</i> Classic sign of [[hypothyroidism]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Mnemonic: \"S1, S2, buckle my shoe\" (Achilles reflex).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Achilles Reflex</b> primarily tests the integrity of the <b>S1</b> nerve root and the tibial nerve; loss suggests pathology at this level or peripheral neuropathy.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
