      "definition": "<p><b>Axonal Injury</b> triggers specific cellular responses: <u>Wallerian Degeneration</u> occurs distal to the lesion (axonal breakdown), while the cell body undergoes the <u>Axonal Reaction</u> (central chromatolysis) to support regeneration.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Wallerian Degeneration (Distal):</b><br> - Degeneration of axon and myelin sheath distal to injury.<br> - Macrophages remove debris.<br> - <i>PNS:</i> Schwann cells promote regeneration.<br> - <i>CNS:</i> Oligodendrocytes/Astrocytes inhibit regeneration (glial scar).</li><li><b>Axonal Reaction (Proximal/Soma):</b><br> - <b>Central Chromatolysis:</b> Cell body swells, nucleus moves to periphery, Nissl substance disperses.<br> - <i>Purpose:</i> Increased protein synthesis for repair.</li><li><b>Diffuse Axonal Injury (DAI):</b> Traumatic shearing of white matter tracts (e.g., rapid deceleration). MRI shows punctate hemorrhages (gray-white junction). Major cause of coma/PVS.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> \"Chromatolysis\" looks like the cell is falling apart, but it's actually revving up for repair.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Axonal Injury</b> leads to distal Wallerian degeneration and proximal central chromatolysis; regeneration is possible in the PNS (Schwann cells) but inhibited in the CNS (glial scar).</p>",
