      "definition": "<p>The <b>Babinski Reflex</b> is a primitive reflex elicited by stroking the lateral sole of the foot; a \"positive\" sign (dorsiflexion/extension of the big toe and fanning of other toes) indicates <u>Upper Motor Neuron (UMN)</u> dysfunction in adults.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Normal Response (Adult):</b> Plantar flexion (down-going toes).</li><li><b>Positive Sign (Pathologic):</b> <b>Dorsiflexion</b> (up-going) of the great toe + fanning of toes.</li><li><b>Significance:</b> Specific sign of <b>Upper Motor Neuron</b> (corticospinal tract) lesion.</li><li><b>Infants:</b> Positive Babinski is <b>normal</b> in infants up to ~12 months due to incomplete myelination of the corticospinal tracts.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Presence of Babinski sign rules out LMN lesion (which would cause flaccid paralysis/areflexia).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Babinski Sign</b> is the quintessential sign of corticospinal tract (UMN) dysfunction in adults, though it is physiologic in infants prior to myelination.</p>",
