      "definition": "<p>The <b>Basement Membrane</b> is a specialized extracellular matrix sheet composed primarily of <u>Type IV collagen</u>, laminin, and proteoglycans, anchoring epithelium to connective tissue and functioning as a selective filtration barrier.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Components:</b> Type <b>IV</b> Collagen (floor), Laminin, Fibronectin, Entactin.</li><li><b>Functions:</b> Cell anchorage, filtration (Kidney), scaffold for regeneration.</li><li><b>Pathology:</b><br> - <b>[[alport_syndrome]]:</b> Defect in Type IV collagen (splitting of GBM) &rarr; Hematuria, Deafness.<br> - <b>[[goodpasture_syndrome]]:</b> Autoantibodies against Type IV collagen (Anti-GBM) &rarr; Hematuria, Hemoptysis.</li><li><b>Blood-Brain Barrier:</b> Fused basement membrane of endothelial cells and astrocyte foot processes.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Type <b>IV</b> collagen is under the <b>Floor</b> (Basement membrane).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Basement Membrane</b> relies on Type IV collagen for structural integrity; defects lead to Alport syndrome, while autoimmune attack causes Goodpasture syndrome.</p>",
