    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Basilar Artery</b> is a major midline vessel formed by the confluence of the two [[vertebral_artery|vertebral arteries]], supplying the brainstem, cerebellum, and posterior cerebrum before bifurcating into the posterior cerebral arteries (PCA).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Formation:</b> Junction of vertebral arteries at the pontomedullary junction.</li><li><b>Branches:</b> [[anterior_inferior_cerebellar_artery]] (AICA), Pontine arteries, [[superior_cerebellar_artery]] (SCA), [[posterior_cerebral_artery]] (PCA).</li><li><b>Stroke Syndromes:</b><br> - <b>Locked-in Syndrome:</b> Basilar artery thrombosis affecting the ventral pons (bilateral corticospinal/bulbar tracts). Preserves vertical eye movements (CN III) and consciousness (RAS).<br> - <b>Top of the Basilar Syndrome:</b> Embolus to top of basilar &rarr; Ischemia of midbrain/thalamus/temporal/occipital lobes (hallucinations, blindness, consciousness issues).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Patient is paralyzed but can blink and look up? Think <b>Basilar</b> thrombosis (Locked-in).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Basilar Artery</b> is the lifeline of the brainstem; occlusion can lead to the catastrophic Locked-in Syndrome, sparing only vertical gaze and consciousness.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Vertebral Arteries] --> B[Basilar Artery]; B --> C[AICA]; B --> D[Pontine Arteries]; B --> E[Superior Cerebellar Arteries]; B --> F[Posterior Cerebral Arteries];"
