      "definition": "<p><b>REM Sleep Behavior Disorder (RBD)</b> is a parasomnia characterized by the <u>loss of normal muscle atonia</u> during REM sleep, resulting in the physical enactment of vivid, often unpleasant dreams.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Dysfunction of brainstem nuclei (e.g., perilocus coeruleus) that normally inhibit spinal motor neurons during REM.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Punching, kicking, yelling during sleep; patient recalls the dream if awakened.</li><li><b>Associations:</b> Strong predictor of <b>Synucleinopathies</b>: [[parkinson_disease]], [[lewy_body_dementia]], Multiple System Atrophy (MSA). Can precede motor symptoms by decades.</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> Clonazepam, Melatonin.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> An elderly man \"acting out dreams\" is a harbinger of Lewy Body Dementia or Parkinson's.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>REM Sleep Behavior Disorder</b> involves the failure of REM atonia and is a specific prodromal marker for alpha-synuclein neurodegenerative diseases like Parkinson's and Lewy Body Dementia.</p>",
