      "definition": "<p><b>Benzocaine</b> is an ester local anesthetic commonly used topically (e.g., for sunburns or throat pain) that is notable for its ability to oxidize hemoglobin, causing [[methemoglobinemia]].</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism:</b> Blocks voltage-gated [[sodium_channel]]s &rarr; blocks nerve conduction.</li><li><b>Adverse Effect:</b> <b>Methemoglobinemia</b> (Oxidizes Fe<sup>2+</sup> to Fe<sup>3+</sup>).</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Cyanosis, \"Chocolate-colored blood\", shortness of breath, normal PaO<sub>2</sub> but low SaO<sub>2</sub>.</li><li><b>Treatment of Toxicity:</b> [[methylene_blue]] (reduces Fe<sup>3+</sup> back to Fe<sup>2+</sup>).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Look for a patient using throat spray or topical analgesic who suddenly turns blue.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Benzocaine</b> is a topical ester anesthetic with the specific board-relevant side effect of inducing <mark>methemoglobinemia</mark>, treated with Methylene Blue.</p>",
