    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Blood-Brain Barrier (BBB)</b> is a highly selective semipermeable border that separates the circulating blood from the brain extracellular fluid, formed primarily by endothelial <u>tight junctions</u> and supported by <u>astrocyte foot processes</u>.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Components:</b><br> 1. <b>Tight Junctions:</b> Between non-fenestrated capillary endothelial cells (prevent paracellular diffusion).<br> 2. <b>Basement Membrane.</b><br> 3. <b>Astrocyte Foot Processes:</b> Induce and maintain tight junctions.</li><li><b>Function:</b> Protects CNS from toxins/pathogens; maintains homeostasis. Allows diffusion of lipid-soluble substances (O2, CO2, ethanol) and carrier-mediated transport of glucose/amino acids.</li><li><b>Disruption:</b> Inflammation (vasogenic edema), Infarction, Osmotic injury.</li><li><b>Exceptions (Circumventricular Organs):</b> Area Postrema (vomiting), OVLT (osmolarity), Neurohypophysis (ADH release) lack a strict BBB.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>BBB</b> strictly regulates CNS entry via endothelial tight junctions and astrocyte foot processes; breakdown leads to vasogenic edema.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Capillary Endothelium] -->|Tight Junctions| B[Barrier Function]; C[Astrocytes] -->|Foot Processes| B; D[Lipid Soluble Molecules] -->|Diffuse| E[Brain Parenchyma]; F[Polar Molecules] --x|Blocked| E;"
    },
