      "definition": "<p>The <b>Blood-Nerve Permeability Barrier</b> is a physiologic barrier within the peripheral nervous system, formed by tight junctions in the endoneurial capillaries and the <u>perineurium</u>, protecting axons from plasma constituents.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Location:</b> Endoneurial microvessels and the inner layers of the [[perineurium]].</li><li><b>Function:</b> Maintains a stable endoneurial microenvironment for nerve conduction.</li><li><b>Pathology:</b> Breakdown leads to leakage of plasma proteins into the endoneurium.</li><li><b>Clinical Relevance:</b> In [[guillain_barre_syndrome]], inflammation disrupts this barrier at the nerve roots, leading to high CSF protein without cells ([[albuminocytologic_dissociation]]).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Blood-Nerve Barrier</b> protects peripheral nerves; its disruption contributes to the high protein levels seen in inflammatory neuropathies like GBS.</p>",
