    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>A <b>Blown Pupil</b> (Fixed and Dilated Pupil) represents a loss of parasympathetic innervation to the sphincter pupillae muscle, resulting in unopposed sympathetic tone and mydriasis, classically caused by compression of the <u>Oculomotor Nerve (CN III)</u>.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Parasympathetic fibers run superficially on CN III. External compression affects these fibers first.</li><li><b>Etiologies:</b><br> - <b>Uncal Herniation:</b> Medial temporal lobe pushes against the tentorium, compressing CN III.<br> - <b>PCom Aneurysm:</b> [[posterior_communicating_artery]] aneurysm compresses CN III.</li><li><b>Clinical Context:</b> \"Down-and-out\" eye with a dilated, non-reactive pupil.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> <br> - <i>Surgical Rule:</i> Pupil-involving CN III palsy = Aneurysm/Herniation (Compression).<br> - <i>Medical Rule:</i> Pupil-sparing CN III palsy = Diabetes (Ischemia of deep motor fibers).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>A <b>Blown Pupil</b> indicates compression of the superficial parasympathetic fibers of CN III, a neurosurgical emergency often signaling uncal herniation or a PCom aneurysm.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Mass Effect / Aneurysm] --> B[External Compression of CN III]; B --> C[Damage to Superficial Parasympathetics]; C --> D[Loss of Constriction]; D --> E[Unopposed Dilation (Blown Pupil)];"
