    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>A <b>Blowout Fracture</b> is a fracture of the orbital floor (maxillary bone) or medial wall (ethmoid bone) caused by blunt trauma to the globe, leading to herniation of orbital contents into the maxillary sinus.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Sudden increase in intraorbital pressure \"blows out\" the thin orbital floor.</li><li><b>Clinical Features:</b><br> - <b>Diplopia:</b> Due to entrapment of the [[inferior_rectus_muscle]] (restriction of upward gaze).<br> - <b>Enophthalmos:</b> Sunken eye.<br> - <b>Infraorbital Anesthesia:</b> Damage to the [[infraorbital_nerve]] (numbness of cheek/upper lip).</li><li><b>Imaging:</b> CT Scan shows \"teardrop sign\" (herniated fat/muscle in sinus).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Look for a patient punched in the eye who cannot look up and has a numb cheek.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Blowout Fractures</b> typically involve the orbital floor, causing entrapment of the inferior rectus (diplopia on upgaze) and injury to the infraorbital nerve (cheek numbness).</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Blunt Trauma to Globe] --> B[Increased Intraorbital Pressure]; B --> C[Fracture of Orbital Floor]; C --> D[Herniation of Contents]; D --> E[Inferior Rectus Entrapment]; E --> F[Diplopia / Gaze Restriction];"
