      "definition": "<p><b>Brain Death</b> is the irreversible cessation of all functions of the entire brain, including the brainstem, characterized clinically by <u>coma</u>, <u>absent brainstem reflexes</u>, and <u>apnea</u>.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Complete loss of cerebral perfusion (Cerebral Perfusion Pressure = MAP - ICP = 0).</li><li><b>Clinical Criteria:</b><br> 1. Coma (unresponsive).<br> 2. Absence of Brainstem Reflexes (Pupillary, Corneal, Oculocephalic, Gag/Cough).<br> 3. Apnea Test (No respiratory drive despite hypercapnia).</li><li><b>Ethical/Legal:</b> Legally equivalent to death. Artificial support can be withdrawn.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Spinal reflexes (e.g., DTRs) may remain intact because they are mediated by the spinal cord, not the brain.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Brain Death</b> is a clinical diagnosis of irreversible total brain failure defined by coma, apnea, and absent brainstem reflexes, often resulting from zero cerebral perfusion pressure.</p>",
