    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Brainstem</b> is the caudal part of the brain, connecting the cerebrum, cerebellum, and spinal cord, composed of the <u>Midbrain</u>, <u>Pons</u>, and <u>Medulla Oblongata</u>; it houses cranial nerve nuclei and vital respiratory/cardiovascular centers.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Components:</b><br> - <b>Midbrain (Mesencephalon):</b> CN III, IV. Vertical gaze, auditory/visual relays.<br> - <b>Pons (Metencephalon):</b> CN V, VI, VII, VIII. Horizontal gaze center (PPRF).<br> - <b>Medulla (Myelencephalon):</b> CN IX, X, XII. Respiratory/Cardiac centers.</li><li><b>Rule of 4s:</b><br> - 4 CNs in Medulla, 4 in Pons, 4 above (2 in midbrain).<br> - Midline structures (Motor) start with <b>M</b> (Motor pathway, Medial Lemniscus, MLF, Motor nuclei 3,4,6,12).<br> - Side structures (Sensory) start with <b>S</b> (Spinothalamic, Spinocerebellar, Sensory V, Sympathetic).</li><li><b>Vascular Supply:</b> Vertebrobasilar system.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Brainstem</b> is the vital conduit for all ascending/descending tracts and the origin of CN III-XII, organized such that medial lesions cause motor deficits and lateral lesions cause sensory/autonomic deficits (Rule of 4s).</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Brainstem] --> B[Midbrain]; A --> C[Pons]; A --> D[Medulla]; B --> E[CN III, IV]; C --> F[CN V, VI, VII, VIII]; D --> G[CN IX, X, XII];"
