      "definition": "<p>The <b>Chemoreceptor Trigger Zone (CTZ)</b> is a specialized area located in the [[area_postrema]] on the floor of the fourth ventricle that lacks a blood-brain barrier, allowing it to detect emetic toxins in the blood and CSF to initiate vomiting.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Location:</b> Area Postrema (Dorsal Medulla).</li><li><b>Function:</b> Senses chemical emetics (drugs, toxins, ketoacidosis, uremia) &rarr; Activates the [[vomiting_center]] (Nucleus Tractus Solitarius).</li><li><b>Receptors:</b> Dopamine (D2), Serotonin (5-HT3), Neurokinin (NK1).</li><li><b>Pharmacology:</b> <br> - <i>Antiemetics:</i> [[ondansetron]] (5-HT3 antagonist), [[metoclopramide]] (D2 antagonist), [[aprepitant]] (NK1 antagonist).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Dopamine agonists (e.g., for Parkinson's) stimulate the CTZ causing nausea.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>CTZ</b> is the brain's chemical sensor for vomiting, accessible to systemic drugs due to the lack of a BBB, and is the primary target for antiemetic therapy.</p>",
