    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Cushing Reflex</b> (or Cushing Response/Triad) is a physiological nervous system response to <u>increased intracranial pressure (ICP)</u> that results in the triad of <b>hypertension</b>, <b>bradycardia</b>, and <b>irregular respirations</b>.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism:</b> Increased ICP compromises [[cerebral_perfusion_pressure]] (CPP) &rarr; Hypothalamus/Brainstem detect ischemia &rarr; Massive Sympathetic discharge &rarr; Peripheral vasoconstriction &rarr; <b>Hypertension</b> (to maintain CPP).</li><li><b>Reflex Bradycardia:</b> Hypertension stimulates [[carotid_sinus]] baroreceptors &rarr; Vagal stimulation &rarr; <b>Bradycardia</b>.</li><li><b>Respiratory Depression:</b> Brainstem compression affects respiratory centers &rarr; Irregular breathing (Cheyne-Stokes or apnea).</li><li><b>Clinical Significance:</b> Sign of <b>impending brain herniation</b>. Immediate intervention required (Hyperventilation, Mannitol).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> High BP + Low HR = Cushing Reflex (High ICP). Low BP + High HR = Shock.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Cushing Reflex</b> is a last-ditch autonomic effort to preserve cerebral perfusion in the face of lethal intracranial hypertension, manifesting as hypertension and reflex bradycardia.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Increased ICP] --> B[Decreased Cerebral Perfusion]; B --> C[Brainstem Ischemia]; C --> D[Sympathetic Surge]; D --> E[Hypertension]; E --> F[Baroreceptor Activation]; F --> G[Vagal Output]; G --> H[Bradycardia];"
