      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism:</b> Ischemia &rarr; ATP depletion &rarr; Na<sup>+</sup>/K<sup>+</sup> pump failure &rarr; Na<sup>+</sup> accumulates inside cell &rarr; Water follows &rarr; Cell swelling.</li><li><b>Location:</b> Affects both <b>Gray and White Matter</b>.</li><li><b>Radiology:</b> Loss of gray-white matter differentiation on CT.</li><li><b>Timing:</b> Occurs within minutes to hours of stroke/injury (Early phase).</li><li><b>Contrast:</b> [[vasogenic_edema]] involves extracellular fluid due to BBB breakdown (Tumors/Late ischemia) and affects white matter predominantly.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Cytotoxic Edema</b> represents cellular swelling due to pump failure in early ischemia, distinguishing it from the vascular leakage of vasogenic edema.</p>",
