    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Depolarizing Neuromuscular Blockers</b> are agents that act as acetylcholine agonists at the neuromuscular junction, causing initial depolarization (fasciculations) followed by desensitization and flaccid paralysis.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Prototype:</b> [[succinylcholine]].</li><li><b>Phase I Block:</b> Sustained depolarization. Na<sup>+</sup> channels remain inactivated. <b>Potentiated</b> by AChE inhibitors. Fasciculations observed.</li><li><b>Phase II Block:</b> Desensitization. Receptors become insensitive to ACh. Resembles nondepolarizing block. <b>Reversed</b> by AChE inhibitors (e.g., [[neostigmine]]).</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> [[malignant_hyperthermia]], Hyperkalemia (risk in burns/trauma), Myalgia.</li><li><b>Metabolism:</b> Hydrolyzed by plasma pseudocholinesterase.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Depolarizing Blockers</b> like Succinylcholine cause paralysis via sustained depolarization; they have two phases of block and carry a risk of hyperkalemia and malignant hyperthermia.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
