    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Diabetic Retinopathy</b> is a retinal microangiopathy caused by chronic hyperglycemia, classified into <u>Non-Proliferative</u> (vascular damage) and <u>Proliferative</u> (neovascularization) stages, serving as a leading cause of blindness.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Glycation/Sorbitol &rarr; Pericyte loss &rarr; Microaneurysms &rarr; Ischemia &rarr; VEGF release &rarr; Neovascularization.</li><li><b>Non-Proliferative (NPDR):</b> Microaneurysms, Dot-blot hemorrhages, <b>[[cotton_wool_spots]]</b> (nerve fiber infarcts), Hard exudates (lipids), Macular edema.</li><li><b>Proliferative (PDR):</b> Chronic hypoxia leads to <b>Neovascularization</b> (new vessels). Risk of vitreous hemorrhage and tractional [[retinal_detachment]].</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> Glucose control, Anti-VEGF (e.g., Bevacizumab), Laser photocoagulation.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> \"Cotton-wool spots\" indicate ischemia. \"New vessels\" define Proliferative disease.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Diabetic Retinopathy</b> progresses from microvascular damage (NPDR: exudates/hemorrhages) to ischemia-driven neovascularization (PDR), treated by targeting VEGF or laser coagulation.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Hyperglycemia] --> B[Pericyte Loss]; B --> C[Microaneurysms]; C --> D[Retinal Ischemia]; D --> E[VEGF Upregulation]; E --> F[Neovascularization (Proliferative)];"
