    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Cholinergic Toxidrome</b> is a constellation of symptoms caused by excessive stimulation of muscarinic and nicotinic receptors due to acetylcholine accumulation, classically seen with [[organophosphates]] or [[cholinesterase_inhibitors]].</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Etiology:</b> Organophosphates (insecticides, nerve gas), Carbamates (Physostigmine, Neostigmine).</li><li><b>Muscarinic Signs (DUMBELS):</b> <b>D</b>iarrhea, <b>U</b>rination, <b>M</b>iosis, <b>B</b>radycardia/Bronchospasm, <b>E</b>mesis, <b>L</b>acrimation, <b>S</b>alivation/Sweating.</li><li><b>Nicotinic Signs:</b> Muscle fasciculations, weakness/paralysis (depolarizing block).</li><li><b>Treatment:</b><br> 1. <b>[[atropine]]:</b> Blocks Muscarinic effects (life-saving for bradycardia/secretions).<br> 2. <b>[[pralidoxime]] (2-PAM):</b> Regenerates AChE (reverses Nicotinic paralysis) if given early (before \"aging\").</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> \"Leaking from every orifice\" = Cholinergic. Atropine fixes the leaks (Muscarinic), 2-PAM fixes the weakness (Nicotinic).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Cholinergic Toxicity</b> presents as \"DUMBELS\" (wet/leaky) due to muscarinic excess and paralysis due to nicotinic excess; Atropine treats the former, Pralidoxime the latter.</p>",
