      "definition": "<p><b>Diazepam</b> (Valium) is a long-acting <i>benzodiazepine</i> that potentiates GABA<sub>A</sub> receptor activity, used for anxiety, muscle spasms, seizures, and alcohol withdrawal.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism:</b> Increases <b>frequency</b> of Cl<sup>-</sup> channel opening at GABA<sub>A</sub> receptors.</li><li><b>Pharmacokinetics:</b> Long half-life with active metabolites. Hepatic metabolism.</li><li><b>Clinical Uses:</b> [[status_epilepticus]] (acute), [[alcohol_withdrawal]], Muscle spasticity/spasms, Anxiety.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Sedation, dependence, respiratory depression.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Useful for tapering alcohol withdrawal due to its self-tapering long half-life. Avoid in liver failure (use Lorazepam instead).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Diazepam</b> is a long-acting benzo ideal for muscle relaxation and preventing withdrawal seizures, mediating inhibition via the GABA-A receptor.</p>",
