    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Diffuse Axonal Injury (DAI)</b> is a severe form of traumatic brain injury caused by <u>shearing forces</u> from rapid acceleration/deceleration (e.g., car accidents), leading to widespread axonal damage particularly at the gray-white matter junction.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism:</b> Shearing/tearing of axons due to rotational forces.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Immediate coma or persistent vegetative state after trauma, often with disproportionately normal initial CT.</li><li><b>Imaging:</b> MRI is more sensitive. Shows multiple punctate micro-hemorrhages, typically at the <b>Gray-White Junction</b>, Corpus Callosum, and Brainstem.</li><li><b>Pathology:</b> Axonal swelling (spheroids), interruption of transport.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Patient in a coma after a high-speed MVA with a \"normal\" CT scan -> Suspect DAI.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Diffuse Axonal Injury</b> is a devastating TBI caused by shearing forces, diagnosed by MRI showing punctate hemorrhages at white matter tracts, often resulting in poor neurologic outcomes.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
