    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>47,XYY Syndrome</b> is a sex chromosome aneuploidy characterized by the presence of an extra Y chromosome in males, resulting from nondisjunction during paternal meiosis II.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Karyotype:</b> 47,XYY.</li><li><b>Clinical Features:</b> Phenotypically <b>normal male</b>. May be <b>very tall</b>, have severe acne, and mild learning disabilities or behavioral problems (impulsivity).</li><li><b>Fertility:</b> Normal fertility (unlike [[klinefelter_syndrome]]).</li><li><b>Pathogenesis:</b> Paternal nondisjunction at Meiosis II (YY sperm).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Often diagnosed incidentally. Differentiate from Klinefelter (47,XXY) which presents with hypogonadism/infertility.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>47,XYY Syndrome</b> affects tall males with normal fertility and variable behavioral issues, caused by paternal meiosis II nondisjunction.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "caused_by",
        "to": "nondisjunction"
      },
      {
        "type": "is_distinguished_from",
        "to": "klinefelter_syndrome"
      }
    ]
  },
  "dream_enactment_behavior": {
    "title": "Dream Enactment Behavior",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Sleep Medicine",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology",
      "Sleep Disorders",
      "Parasomnias"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Dream Enactment Behavior</b> is the hallmark clinical finding of [[rem_sleep_behavior_disorder]], characterized by the loss of normal REM muscle atonia, allowing patients to physically act out vivid, often violent dreams.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism:</b> Dysfunction of brainstem nuclei (sublaterodorsal nucleus) that normally mediate REM atonia.</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Punching, kicking, yelling, or leaping from bed during REM sleep.</li><li><b>Associations:</b> Highly predictive of alpha-synucleinopathies: [[parkinson_disease]], [[lewy_body_dementia]], and [[multiple_system_atrophy]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> If an elderly patient \"fights in his sleep,\" suspect a developing synucleinopathy.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Dream Enactment</b> signifies a breakdown in REM atonia and is a strong prodromal sign for neurodegenerative diseases like Parkinson's.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
