  "dystonia": {
    "title": "Dystonia",
    "primaryType": "finding",
    "tags": [
      "Neurology",
      "Movement Disorders",
      "Pathology",
      "USMLE"
    ],
    "classificationPath": [
      "Neurology",
      "Movement Disorders",
      "Hyperkinetic"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Dystonia</b> is a movement disorder characterized by sustained or repetitive muscle contractions leading to abnormal, twisting postures or repetitive movements.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Features:</b> Involuntary, patterned, sustained. Often worsened by voluntary movement.</li><li><b>Examples:</b><br> - <i>Focal:</i> Torticollis (Cervical), Blepharospasm (Eyelids), Writer's Cramp.<br> - <i>Acute Dystonic Reaction:</i> Oculogyric crisis/Torticollis post-antipsychotics (Treat with [[benztropine]]).<br> - <i>Generalized:</i> DYT1 mutation.</li><li><b>Localization:</b> Basal Ganglia dysfunction.</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> Anticholinergics ([[benztropine]]), [[botulinum_toxin]] (focal), Muscle relaxants ([[baclofen]]).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> \"Torticollis\" or \"Writer's Cramp\" = Focal Dystonia. Acute onset after Haloperidol = Acute Dystonia (Treat with Diphenhydramine/Benztropine).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Dystonia</b> involves sustained twisting muscle contractions; acute drug-induced forms respond rapidly to anticholinergics, while chronic focal forms are treated with botulinum toxin.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
        "type": "treated_by",
