      "definition": "<p>The <b>Edinger-Westphal Nucleus</b> is the visceral accessory nucleus of the [[oculomotor_nerve]] located in the midbrain, serving as the source of preganglionic <u>parasympathetic</u> fibers that control pupillary constriction and lens accommodation.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Location:</b> Dorsal Midbrain, rostral to the Oculomotor Nucleus.</li><li><b>Input:</b> Pretectal nuclei (Light Reflex), Visual Cortex (Accommodation).</li><li><b>Output:</b> Preganglionic parasympathetic fibers travel with CN III &rarr; [[ciliary_ganglion]].</li><li><b>Function:</b> Innervates Sphincter Pupillae (Miosis) and Ciliary Muscle (Accommodation).</li><li><b>Clinical Relevance:</b> Damage results in a dilated, fixed pupil (loss of parasympathetic tone).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> In [[argyll_robertson_pupil]] (Neurosyphilis), the pretectal input is damaged (no light reflex), but cortical input remains (accommodation intact).</li></ul>",
