      "definition": "<p><b>Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome (EDS)</b> is a heterogeneous group of connective tissue disorders caused by defects in <u>collagen synthesis</u> or processing, characterized by tissue fragility, skin hyperextensibility, and joint hypermobility.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Mutations in Collagen (Type III or V) or processing enzymes (e.g., procollagen peptidase).</li><li><b>Clinical Features:</b> Stretchy skin, easy bruising, joint dislocations, poor wound healing (\"cigarette paper\" scars).</li><li><b>Vascular Type (Type IV):</b> Mutation in <b>Type III Collagen</b> (<i>COL3A1</i>). Risk of <b>[[saccular_aneurysm]]</b>, organ rupture (uterus, bowel), and [[aortic_dissection]].</li><li><b>Classic Type:</b> Mutation in <b>Type V Collagen</b> (<i>COL5A1/2</i>). Skin/Joint symptoms predominant.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Differentiate from [[marfan_syndrome]]: Marfan has tall stature/lens dislocation (Fibrillin); EDS has stretchy skin/easy bruising (Collagen).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome</b> involves defective collagen, leading to structural weakness; the Vascular type is particularly dangerous due to the risk of spontaneous [[saccular_aneurysm]] rupture.</p>",
