    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Embolic Stroke</b> is a type of ischemic stroke caused by a blood clot or debris traveling from a distant site (usually the heart or carotids) and lodging in a cerebral artery, typically characterized by <u>sudden onset</u> of maximal deficits.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Etiologies:</b><br> - <i>Cardiac:</i> [[atrial_fibrillation]], mural thrombus (post-MI), infective endocarditis (septic emboli), [[patent_foramen_ovale]] (paradoxical embolus).<br> - <i>Arterial:</i> Carotid plaque rupture.</li><li><b>Territory:</b> Often affects <b>multiple vascular territories</b> or the [[middle_cerebral_artery]] (largest target).</li><li><b>Imaging:</b> CT may show wedge-shaped infarcts at the gray-white junction (cortical).</li><li><b>Clinical:</b> Abrupt onset symptoms (unlike thrombotic, which may stutter).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> A patient with \"sudden onset\" aphasia and a history of \"palpitations\" (A-fib) likely has an embolic stroke.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Embolic Strokes</b> are acute ischemic events originating largely from cardiac sources (like A-fib), producing sudden, often cortical, neurologic deficits.</p>",
