      "definition": "<p><b>Entacapone</b> is a <u>peripheral</u> <i>COMT inhibitor</i> (Catechol-O-methyltransferase) used as an adjunct to [[carbidopa_levodopa]] in Parkinson's disease to prolong the half-life of Levodopa.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism:</b> Inhibits peripheral COMT &rarr; Prevents degradation of L-DOPA to 3-O-methyldopa (3-OMD) &rarr; Increases L-DOPA availability to cross the BBB.</li><li><b>Permeability:</b> Does <b>NOT</b> cross the BBB (unlike [[tolcapone]]).</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> [[parkinson_disease]] (specifically to reduce \"wearing-off\" effects of Levodopa).</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Enhances L-DOPA toxicity (dyskinesia, nausea), orange discoloration of urine. No hepatotoxicity (unlike Tolcapone).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> <b>Ent</b>acapone enters only the <b>Ent</b>eric system (Peripheral). <b>Tol</b>capone takes a <b>Tol</b>l on the liver (Central + Peripheral).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Entacapone</b> extends the duration of Levodopa action by inhibiting its peripheral breakdown, useful for motor fluctuations in Parkinson's without the liver toxicity of Tolcapone.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Levodopa] -->|COMT| B[3-OMD (Inactive)]; A -->|BBB| C[CNS Levodopa]; D[Entacapone] --x|Inhibits| A; A -->|Increased| C;"
