      "definition": "<p>The <b>Epidural Space</b> is the anatomical compartment located between the <u>dura mater</u> and the vertebral wall (in the spine) or the skull (in the cranium), containing fat and the internal vertebral venous plexus.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Spinal Epidural Space:</b> A <i>real</i> space containing fat and veins. Target for <b>Epidural Anesthesia</b> (needle passes through Ligamentum Flavum to reach it).</li><li><b>Cranial Epidural Space:</b> A <i>potential</i> space between the skull and the periosteal layer of the dura. Site of [[epidural_hematoma]] (Middle Meningeal Artery rupture).</li><li><b>Clinical Relevance:</b> <br> - <b>Anesthesia:</b> Injection of local anesthetics/opioids.<br> - <b>Hemorrhage:</b> Arterial bleed creates a biconvex mass.<br> - <b>Abscess:</b> Spinal epidural abscess.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> During a lumbar puncture, the needle passes through the Ligamentum Flavum <i>before</i> entering the Epidural Space (often stopping there for epidural, or continuing through Dura for spinal tap).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Epidural Space</b> is a real fat-filled space in the spine used for anesthesia, but a potential space in the cranium where arterial hematomas form.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Skin] --> B[Supraspinous Ligament]; B --> C[Interspinous Ligament]; C --> D[Ligamentum Flavum]; D --> E[Epidural Space]; E --> F[Dura Mater]; F --> G[Subarachnoid Space];"
    },
