    "content": {
      "definition": "<p>The <b>Epineurium</b> is the dense, irregular connective tissue layer that surrounds the <u>entire peripheral nerve</u> trunk, binding multiple nerve fascicles together and containing the nutrient blood vessels (vasa nervorum).</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Location:</b> Outermost layer of a peripheral nerve.</li><li><b>Function:</b> Structural support, protection, and housing for blood supply.</li><li><b>Hierarchy:</b> <br> 1. <b>Epineurium:</b> Surrounds entire nerve.<br> 2. [[perineurium]]: Surrounds fascicles (Blood-Nerve Barrier).<br> 3. [[endoneurium]]: Surrounds individual axons.</li><li><b>Clinical Relevance:</b> Often sutured during surgical nerve repair (neurorrhaphy).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Epineurium</b> is the tough outer sheath of a peripheral nerve, encasing fascicles wrapped in perineurium and axons wrapped in endoneurium.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Peripheral Nerve] --> B[Epineurium]; B --> C[Fascicles]; C --> D[Perineurium]; D --> E[Axons]; E --> F[Endoneurium];"
