    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Esotropia</b> is a form of [[strabismus]] characterized by the inward deviation (convergence) of one or both eyes (\"crossed eyes\"), potentially leading to amblyopia if untreated.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Presentation:</b> Eye turns <b>inward</b> toward the nose.</li><li><b>Etiologies:</b><br> - <b>Congenital:</b> Infantile esotropia.<br> - <b>Accommodative:</b> Due to uncorrected [[hyperopia]] (farsightedness) causing excessive convergence.<br> - <b>Paralytic:</b> [[abducens_nerve]] (CN VI) palsy (Lateral Rectus weakness).</li><li><b>Complications:</b> [[amblyopia]] (brain suppresses image from deviating eye), loss of binocular vision/stereopsis.</li><li><b>Treatment:</b> Glasses (for accommodative), Patching (for amblyopia), Surgery.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Esotropia</b> is inward eye deviation; in children, it requires prompt correction to prevent permanent cortical visual loss ([[amblyopia]]), while in adults, it often signals CN VI palsy.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
