    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Essential Tremor</b> is the most common movement disorder, characterized by a high-frequency <u>action</u> and <u>postural</u> tremor of the upper extremities (and often head/voice) that worsens with movement and anxiety.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Features:</b> <b>Action tremor</b> (worsens when holding a posture or reaching for a target). Bilateral. Improves with <b>Alcohol</b>.</li><li><b>Genetics:</b> Often familial (Autosomal Dominant).</li><li><b>Differentiation:</b> Contrast with [[parkinson_disease]] (Resting tremor, pill-rolling, gets <i>better</i> with movement).</li><li><b>Treatment:</b><br> - First-line: <b>[[propranolol]]</b> (Beta-blocker) or <b>[[primidone]]</b> (Barbiturate).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> \"Patient drinks a glass of wine and the shaking stops.\"</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Essential Tremor</b> is a familial action tremor relieved by alcohol and beta-blockers, distinguishing it from the resting tremor of Parkinson's.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
