    "classificationPath": [
      "Pharmacology",
      "Sedative-Hypnotics",
      "Nonbenzodiazepines"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Eszopiclone</b> is a non-benzodiazepine sedative-hypnotic (\"Z-drug\") that acts as an agonist at the BZ1 subtype of the [[gaba_a_receptor]], used for the treatment of insomnia.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism:</b> Binds GABA<sub>A</sub> receptor at a distinct site from benzos; selective for BZ1 subtype (sedation > anxiolysis).</li><li><b>Pharmacokinetics:</b> Rapid onset, relatively short duration. Reversible by [[flumazenil]].</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> Insomnia (difficulty falling or staying asleep).</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> Ataxia, headaches, confusion, metallic taste. Less tolerance/dependence risk than benzodiazepines.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> \"All the <b>Z</b>zzs put you to sleep\" (Zolpidem, Zaleplon, esZopiclone).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Eszopiclone</b> is a Z-drug that induces sleep via GABA<sub>A</sub> modulation with a lower side-effect profile than benzodiazepines, reversible by flumazenil.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
