      "Anticonvulsants"
    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Ethosuximide</b> is a narrow-spectrum anticonvulsant that specifically blocks <u>T-type calcium channels</u> in thalamic neurons, making it the first-line treatment for [[absence_seizure]].</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism:</b> Blocks T-type Ca<sup>2+</sup> channels in the [[thalamus]], disrupting the 3 Hz spike-and-wave rhythmicity.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> <b>Absence Seizures</b> (Petit mal) only. Ineffective for tonic-clonic or focal seizures.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> <b>EFGH:</b> <b>E</b>thosuximide causes <b>F</b>atigue, <b>G</b>I distress, <b>H</b>eadache. Rare: [[stevens_johnson_syndrome]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> If a patient has <i>both</i> absence and tonic-clonic seizures, use [[valproate]] instead (Ethosuximide won't cover the tonic-clonic).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Ethosuximide</b> targets thalamic T-type calcium channels to treat absence seizures exclusively.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
    "connections": [
      {
