    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Etomidate</b> is a short-acting intravenous anesthetic agent that potentiates [[gaba_a_receptor]] activity, favored for induction in hemodynamically unstable patients due to its minimal cardiovascular depression.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Mechanism:</b> Potentiates GABA<sub>A</sub> receptors.</li><li><b>Clinical Use:</b> Rapid Sequence Intubation (RSI), anesthesia induction.</li><li><b>Advantages:</b> <b>Hemodynamic stability</b> (minimal effect on BP/HR/CO). ideal for trauma/shock patients.</li><li><b>Adverse Effects:</b> <b>Adrenal Suppression</b> (inhibits 11&beta;-hydroxylase), Postoperative nausea/vomiting, Myoclonus.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Use in the hypotensive trauma patient, but watch out for adrenal insufficiency.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Etomidate</b> is the induction agent of choice for hemodynamically unstable patients but carries a risk of transient adrenal suppression.</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
