    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Ex Vacuo Ventriculomegaly</b> is the compensatory enlargement of the cerebral ventricles and subarachnoid spaces secondary to the loss of brain tissue (atrophy), rather than increased cerebrospinal fluid pressure.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Pathophysiology:</b> Brain atrophy (neuronal loss) &rarr; Brain shrinks &rarr; CSF fills the empty space.</li><li><b>Intracranial Pressure (ICP):</b> <b>Normal</b>.</li><li><b>Etiologies:</b> [[alzheimer_disease]], [[huntington_disease]], [[frontotemporal_dementia]], HIV-associated dementia, Normal aging.</li><li><b>Imaging:</b> Enlarged ventricles with prominent/widened sulci (cortical atrophy).</li><li><b>Differentiation:</b> Contrast with [[normal_pressure_hydrocephalus]] (Ventricles disproportionately large compared to sulci/atrophy; triad of wet/wobbly/wacky).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Ex Vacuo Ventriculomegaly</b> is an appearance of hydrocephalus caused by brain atrophy, distinguished by normal ICP and proportionate sulcal widening.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[Neurodegeneration] --> B[Cortical Atrophy]; B --> C[Loss of Brain Volume]; C --> D[Passive Expansion of Ventricles]; D --> E[Hydrocephalus Ex Vacuo];"
