    ],
    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Neonatal Extracranial Injuries</b> are traumatic scalp swellings occurring during birth, distinguished by their anatomical location relative to the skull sutures and periosteum.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>[[caput_succedaneum]]:</b> Edema above periosteum. Soft/boggy. <b>Crosses suture lines</b>. Resolves quickly.</li><li><b>[[cephalohematoma]]:</b> Subperiosteal blood. Firm. <b>Bounded by suture lines</b>. Resolves slowly; risk of jaundice.</li><li><b>[[subgaleal_hemorrhage]]:</b> Blood under galea aponeurosis. Diffuse, fluctuant, crosses sutures. <b>Life-threatening</b> (can hold large volume of blood).</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Caput <b>C</b>rosses. Cephalohematoma is <b>C</b>onfined. Subgaleal is <b>S</b>cary.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>Differentiating neonatal scalp swelling relies on suture line boundaries: Caput (crosses, benign), Cephalohematoma (bounded, jaundice risk), Subgaleal (diffuse, hemorrhage risk).</p>",
      "mermaid": ""
    },
