    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Eye Movements</b> are coordinated by the six extraocular muscles, innervated by Cranial Nerves III, IV, and VI, and controlled by brainstem gaze centers.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Innervation Formula:</b> <b>LR6 SO4 R3</b> (Lateral Rectus = CN VI; Superior Oblique = CN IV; Rest = CN III).</li><li><b>Actions:</b><br> - <i>Lateral Rectus:</i> Abduction.<br> - <i>Medial Rectus:</i> Adduction.<br> - <i>Superior Oblique:</i> Intorsion, Depression.<br> - <i>Inferior Oblique:</i> Extorsion, Elevation.<br> - <i>Superior Rectus:</i> Elevation.<br> - <i>Inferior Rectus:</i> Depression.</li><li><b>Gaze Centers:</b><br> - <i>Horizontal:</i> [[paramedian_pontine_reticular_formation]] (PPRF).<br> - <i>Vertical:</i> Rostral interstitial nucleus of MLF (Midbrain).</li><li><b>Pathology:</b> Palsies (CN III down/out; CN IV vertical diplopia/head tilt; CN VI medial deviation).</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Eye Movements</b> depend on the precise coordination of CN III, IV, and VI; dysfunction leads to specific patterns of diplopia and strabismus.</p>",
      "mermaid": "graph TD; A[CN VI] --> B[Lateral Rectus (Abduct)]; C[CN IV] --> D[Superior Oblique (Intort/Depress)]; E[CN III] --> F[Medial/Sup/Inf Recti + Inf Oblique];"
