      "definition": "<p>A <b>Generalized Tonic-Clonic Seizure</b> (Grand Mal) is a type of seizure involving the entire brain, characterized by an initial <u>tonic</u> phase (stiffening, loss of consciousness) followed by a <u>clonic</u> phase (rhythmic jerking), and a postictal state.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Phases:</b><br> 1. <b>Tonic:</b> Sudden loss of consciousness, diffuse muscle contraction (stiffening), \"ictal cry\" (expiration against closed glottis).<br> 2. <b>Clonic:</b> Rhythmic jerking of limbs.<br> 3. <b>Postictal:</b> Confusion, lethargy, gradual return to baseline.</li><li><b>Physiology:</b> Diffuse, synchronous electrical discharges across both hemispheres.</li><li><b>Management:</b> ABCs. Abort with [[benzodiazepines]] if prolonged. Maintenance with [[valproate]], [[levetiracetam]], or [[lamotrigine]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Differentiate from syncope (quick recovery, no postictal confusion). Lateral tongue biting implies seizure.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Tonic-Clonic Seizures</b> are the most dramatic generalized seizures, involving stiffening and jerking followed by profound postictal confusion; they require broad-spectrum anticonvulsants.</p>",
