      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Course:</b> Neck &rarr; Carotid Canal &rarr; <b>Cavernous Sinus</b> (Cavernous Segment) &rarr; Cerebral Circle of Willis.</li><li><b>Relations:</b> Inside the Cavernous Sinus, it runs adjacent to <b>[[abducens_nerve]] (CN VI)</b>. Postganglionic sympathetic fibers run along its surface.</li><li><b>Branches:</b> Ophthalmic Artery, PCom, Anterior Choroidal, Bifurcates into ACA and MCA.</li><li><b>Pathology:</b><br> - <b>Aneurysm (Cavernous):</b> Can compress CN VI (isolated lateral rectus palsy).<br> - <b>Dissection:</b> Painful Horner Syndrome (disrupts sympathetics).<br> - <b>Fistula:</b> [[carotid_cavernous_fistula]].</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p>The <b>Internal Carotid Artery</b> supplies the anterior circulation and passes through the cavernous sinus, where pathology can cause specific deficits like CN VI palsy or Horner syndrome.</p>",
