    "content": {
      "definition": "<p><b>Intraparenchymal Hemorrhage</b> is a subtype of hemorrhagic stroke involving bleeding directly into the brain tissue, most commonly caused by the rupture of small penetrating arteries due to chronic <u>hypertension</u> or <u>amyloid angiopathy</u>.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Etiologies:</b><br> - <b>Hypertensive:</b> Rupture of <b>[[charcot_bouchard_microaneurysm]]</b>. Affects deep structures: Basal Ganglia (Putamen), Thalamus, Pons, Cerebellum.<br> - <b>[[cerebral_amyloid_angiopathy]]:</b> Beta-amyloid deposition in vessels. Affects <b>Lobar</b> (cortical) regions (e.g., Occipital, Parietal). Common in elderly.<br> - <b>Other:</b> AVM, Tumor, Coagulopathy, Vasculitis.</li><li><b>Clinical Features:</b> Sudden onset focal deficit + Headache, Vomiting, Decreased consciousness (mass effect).</li><li><b>Imaging:</b> CT shows hyperdense (white) collection within brain parenchyma.</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> Putaminal hemorrhage causes contralateral hemiparesis (Internal Capsule compression). Pontine hemorrhage causes \"pinpoint pupils\" and coma.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Intraparenchymal Hemorrhage</b> is usually hypertensive (deep/basal ganglia) or amyloid-related (lobar); it causes rapid mass effect and focal deficits based on location.</p>",
