      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>[[propofol]]:</b> Potentiates GABA<sub>A</sub>. Rapid on/off. Anti-emetic. <i>SE:</i> Hypotension, respiratory depression, pain on injection.</li><li><b>[[etomidate]]:</b> Potentiates GABA<sub>A</sub>. Hemodynamically stable. <i>SE:</i> <b>Adrenal suppression</b>.</li><li><b>[[ketamine]]:</b> NMDA antagonist. Dissociative anesthesia. Sympathomimetic (increases BP/HR). <i>SE:</i> Hallucinations, emergence delirium.</li><li><b>[[barbiturates]] (Thiopental):</b> Potentiates GABA<sub>A</sub>. Decreases cerebral blood flow/ICP. Highly lipid soluble (redistributes to tissue).</li><li><b>[[benzodiazepines]] (Midazolam):</b> Potentiates GABA<sub>A</sub>. Amnesia/Sedation. Reversal: Flumazenil.</li><li><b>Opioids:</b> Adjuncts for analgesia.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>IV Anesthetics</b> allow for rapid induction; Propofol is standard, Etomidate is for hemodynamically unstable patients, and Ketamine provides analgesia/sympathetic boost.</p>",
