      "definition": "<p><b>Iron</b> is an essential mineral required for the synthesis of hemoglobin, myoglobin, and cytochromes, with its metabolism tightly regulated by absorption in the duodenum and storage as ferritin.</p>",
      "atAGlance": "<ul><li><b>Absorption:</b> Duodenum (as Fe<sup>2+</sup>). Enhanced by Vitamin C; Inhibited by tannins/tea. Regulated by <b>Hepcidin</b> (blocks ferroportin).</li><li><b>Transport:</b> <b>Transferrin</b> (transports Fe<sup>3+</sup> in blood).</li><li><b>Storage:</b> <b>Ferritin</b> (primary), Hemosiderin (macrophage degradation product).</li><li><b>Pathology:</b><br> - <b>Deficiency:</b> [[iron_deficiency_anemia]] (Microcytic, Low Ferritin, High TIBC).<br> - <b>Overload:</b> [[hemochromatosis]] (Bronze diabetes, cirrhosis, cardiomyopathy).<br> - <b>Toxicity:</b> Acute poisoning (GI bleeding, metabolic acidosis). Treat with [[deferoxamine]].</li><li><b>USMLE Tip:</b> \"Iron OUT\" (High TIBC/Transferrin) in deficiency. \"Iron IN\" (Low TIBC) in chronic disease/overload.</li></ul>",
      "takeAway": "<p><b>Iron</b> is critical for oxygen transport; deficiency leads to microcytic anemia, while overload (Hemochromatosis) causes multiorgan damage due to free radical generation.</p>",
